IBM history: From cheese cutter to all around the world
Founded a century ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
IBM took its name only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company laid the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous ticket numbers for registration of the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also Chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930, became the architect of this new company.
And it was Flint who hired Thomas J. Watson's manager to help him manage the company.
This leader then even put the founder of IBM in the shadows - based on Watson's ideas to this day the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson managed the company until 1952.
IBM, as already the name reveals, began with the production and distribution of all possible machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters, to cash.
In the first four decades that Watson was running the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped manage NASA flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight of man to the Moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the series IBM System/360.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of that time came to the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, she bought the consultancy part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and entered into the business with highly-valued consultancy services and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the last three years is the concept of Smart Planet.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in previously unplanned areas, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform to help retailers manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong story in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932, IBM founded a branch in Czechoslovakia - as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-level top team of researchers dealing with voice recognition technology.
