Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel offices in the then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At the time, the travel offices sold mainly only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, in the West only those who were allowed to choose at that time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when Yugoslavia was also allowed to travel, Yugoslavia took a pro-western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern bloc (also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel to Poland individually or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
The travel agencies also offered travel to the West at the time, but then you had to buy huge snakes or even stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel office.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holiday in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The 1989 revolution followed a journey revolution of the Czechs on their feet.
While a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which one is not even aware of today, is the fact that one could not travel to the current most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Just from the beginning of the 90s of the past century, foreign exchange obligations were lifted in neighbouring Western European countries, which led to a huge wave of short visits, particularly to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could for a long time get from their travels to the West simply not enough, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers slept in the park when traveling to Paris in the tent, because who would have had the money for accommodation at the hotel or in a guest house at that time.
A typical feature of travel abroad from the Czech Republic was a fully packed trunk with canned, beer and permanent sausages etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our level of life and therefore the average salaries rose, which resulted in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, the travel agencies began to regularly prepare journeys through charter flights after 1997, making the journeys impossible thanks to the possibility to negotiate discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, had already currencyless payments with all highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "mail-samtenen" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight in an exotic country was completed - to Thailand.
Every year, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying in far-off sunny countries; this year, 12 exotic destinations are flown directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 thousand Czechs travel every year in exotic countries!
Another important moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17th, 2008, the US lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs first spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 cents per head for a single holiday stay, including the cost at the resort.
