Climate change slowed down the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in the government, in Sinaloa unemployment and undeclared work rose, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloas. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who described himself as the initiator of the change and has built great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, due to the climatic hardships, growth cannot be the talk, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February caused not only losses in the millions of farms, but also close to the growth of the national economy, causing a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter, mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which slowed down the impact on other sectors of the economy.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582,000 hectares of land used for agriculture were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partly destroyed.
The decline in economic activity by November has continuously increased in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, since from January to March, 55,053 people had no employment, corresponding to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa. That is 18,969 people more than in the first quarter.
Low liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year dates back to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented, the policy of the public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, with loss of liquidity in the market due to the cuts in the averages by legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are forbidden to raise dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them, or use anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment rate is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen. This is due, on the one hand, to the entry problems and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work here to increase unemployment," he says.
Blacksmiths' wares
The analysis of the Sinaloa labour market is even more serious if the high proportion of undeclared work is taken into account, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38% of the country's employees who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest wages in the whole of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretariía del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, which is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Reduction of the ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and growing unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretariía de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI from January to June amounted to 630 597 dollars, which corresponds to a drop of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (government agency for economic development) has a total investment of 17,280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from tertiary sector enterprises.
The debt
In view of the economic crisis, in July at the National Congress, the Government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in the reactivation of the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's inadequacy evident.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing in Mexico), stated that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. We need to work hard to regain the terrain lost this year and we need to make double efforts in 2012. The efforts of all and in particular the progress of the well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slow economy, which is not sufficiently in motion to produce economic dynamics that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will conclude the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine Profession
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Companies of Mexico) in Sinaloa, stated that the state should be moved to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the economic profession and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources, Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will steer the government's efforts towards better governance.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
