The Court approved the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
Conversion of analogues to digital signals has been one of the most important changes in the world over the last few years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the presidential decree and called for the transfer of analogues to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 due to a lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the Decree-Law with details on the switchover to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute raised by the Senate, since it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
The project for the appeal, which was drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the Decree-Law for non-constitutional, since the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) was responsible for the regulations concerning radio and television, which would contradict hierarchical principles and legal reservation.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed complaints against the Decree-Law. Following the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree-Law and applied all activities to set up the digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the appeal filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the debate on the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In its contribution, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration by means of general rules.
"I also do not believe that if this were to be done, the independence of the regulatory body would be compromised." She also reminded us that the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because they are responsible for state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in a better use of the radio-electric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the exploitation of digitalisation, which is a decision in the public interest which not only has a technical point of view, "because it covers economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "required the action of the whole system, in accordance with the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features which put the Constitution in the hands of the central government."
It called to mind that many countries around the world had already carried out the digital transformation, even though they had highly specialised institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the government intervened with the publication of the contested decree in the powers of Congress, because the laws adopted by the legislature would be complied with," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots individually in Michoacán is considered.
According to PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is close to 27 percent, with 879 votes in total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of the individual counting of the ballots is a reality this year in the Michoacán elections, because according to the data published by the Programa deResultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the governorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Elekctoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, pointed out that only last November, the electoral office had adopted a number of rules to harmonise local rules with the reforms of the states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force at this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the public prosecutor within the time limits provided for by the argument or objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional appeal filed by the local legislature and judged the representative's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal" since it did not have the right to "adoption or veto".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview about the possibility of the individual counting of votes that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, the possibility now exists that the local electoral authority could either partially or completely list the ballots.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more ballot packages may be partially counted The results of the protocols do not match; the Minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not factually available or are not owned by the Chairman of the Election Committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the protocols.
In addition, if there is a difference between the likely winner and the one standing in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, the total number of full ballots may be counted, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the named candidates.
Votes may also be counted in their entirety if, after completion of the orderly calculation, it is established that the difference between the likely winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages exposed to partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and the second place is about 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of 923 election protocols have not yet been counted.
