MSS announces a research protocol to detect the gene for obesity
The National Social Insurance Institute of Mexico is head of a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is a research project on the discovery of the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Youth" with which genetic markers are to be found in conjunction with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI stated that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the sports places of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are conducted every Saturday from 8.00 p.m.
He stressed that the study started at the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the west of the state of México) and was continued on the Nezahualcóyolt sports field (in the east of the state of México).
If the goal has been reached by 500 to 600 investigators, the study will be continued on the Independencia sports ground (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the one of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He stated that the aim of the study was to identify the factors and role of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors for Mexican children and adolescents to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the global day of diabetes, he stated that it was intended that three thousand children and young people aged six to 14 should be filled in with the consent and under the supervision of their parents’ nutrition questionnaires.
They will also ask questions about their physical activity and their family history in order to control risk factors that may lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
It further stated that on those Saturdays the investigators were measured (weight, size, waist count), their blood pressure controlled and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (test for identification of genes related to childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out on the occasion of health care professionals' concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"Health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years the percentage of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that the girls with obesity increased by 47 percent. The excess weight also increased dramatically," said the specialist of the IMSS.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that a Mexican (in) averaged 65 percent of Indian-American, 30% of European and 5% of African descent, reflecting the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity were preoccupied with the inability to burn out the excess of energy (calorie) taken from us, so that it was stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the investigators was derived from a comprehensive study of the children in which they would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the presence of dark skin folds in the neck and the inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the advanced stage.
All the information would be treated confidentially and communicated in writing to the parents by the doctors. The doctors explain all the measurement results to the parents and suggest to them changes in the lifestyle that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there were three basic factors that are responsible for obesity, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of movement, i.e. lack of movement in everyday life, spending most of the day before the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short paths.
The high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugared drinks and carbohydrates (Tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt by UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM developed modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs that go out of the road surface were to be considered, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 keyholes when the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the UNAM, warned and assured that if the construction and maintenance of the asphalt coating were to be adequately damaged, the number of impact holes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
