When the vehicles continue to move and forces are generated on it, this layer enables a good distribution of power in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a final layer will be laid out, the so-called bearing layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e., sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it needs to produce friction.
The most powerful and distributed of this pavement also requires an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature variations, are other important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain is wetted, water enters the layer and escapes only difficult again. This causes a softening of all strata of the road surface and, as a result, the occurrence of impact holes.
