Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If a topic does not exist on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly the energy policy.
The availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to have an electoral meeting on this subject and to think about the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is leading to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, a huge proportion of the world's population should not have to renounce a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to be able to produce electricity consistently, without the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, to forget an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The accident of Fukushima does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to refrain from nuclear power.
This is neither the case in Belgium, which makes its decision subject to the need to find a substitute source of substitution, nor in Switzerland, which is just about to build nuclear power plants of the last generation.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few countries, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
On the other hand, the United States decided to attract another unit after Fukushima by re-establishing the Three Mile Island plant that was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model is sometimes set as a model for renewable energy sources, reality does contradict the discourse.
The elections in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, particularly on Russia, by means of the increased use of imported gas, a rise in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will already become apparent within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
Denmark, on the one hand, is a European leader in wind energy, from which it derives 30% of its electricity; on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; on the other hand, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill in contrast to our French households.
As the price of energy in the globalised economy is a key role of competitiveness and an industrial stability path on national soils, French companies have an advantage due to the most favourable electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a strong increase in the price of energy, which will lead to the illusion of the noble statements about the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
Surveys showed that this is a price which the vast majority of French people are as unwilling to pay, as it shows resistance to the principle of this source of energy.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has enabled us to build an industrial sector with 125.00 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France were to take the decision to withdraw from nuclear power, the bulk of these SMEs would fall victim to this, and the annual EUR 6 billion of investment and nuclear energy exports would be increasingly shrinking.
What electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if its producer's decline was preprogrammed?
In order to solve the energy equation, one has to admit that there is just as little as a devil's work as a miracle agent for the production of electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by the Areva company for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France we have carried out a safety authority that performs uncompromising and transparent controls in existing works, such as building in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are currently obsessed with the security vision.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one person, in Three Mile Island, entered the market under normal operating conditions, without any consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was challenged by reactor construction as well as indebted human failure.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident of two natural disasters has never been caused by the mass that caused the death of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident, as it had done after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach, as well as the cooperation of the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, the EPR represents a design that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power station, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them free train to travel the leading position in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy boiquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party manoeuvre dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
