But this policy was rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right, Jacques Chirac's tone, which had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including more than 2 million immigrant workers, are not likely to pose a problem for a country," on the left by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990, "could not absorb the whole poverty of the world".
There is only one difference in the degree of inertia.
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by Horden Polish plumber was shared both from the right and from the left in 2005.
From both camps the immigrants were treated as a burden for the economy and the French society.
The only difference is the degree of initiative that immigrants are willing to face.
In his programme, Francois Hollande is limited to banalities, which indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections, but it is economically costly.
As Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron showed us in a recent work that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 S.), there is a broad consensus among specialists regarding the positive impact of the immigrant flood on economic growth, wages and jobs in the countries of immigration.
Immigration would reduce growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitut the local workers, especially the less qualified, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than local wage workers, since they are engaged mainly in occupations in sectors that are technically unexploited.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors where local wage-earners are not interested, the more skilled among immigrants are working in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the job offer.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the influx of immigrants causes a co-related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas gained by immigrants and economic growth is beneficial (high proportion of immigrants who have been resident among American Nobel Laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, in the European countries on average around 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organisation estimates that a person who is aged 30 to Germany makes a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around EUR 150,000 to the public budget on average over his lifetime.
