The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the Baltic seabed and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to perform this event with brilliance and Gloria.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, have lived last Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and at fine-tasting buffets the opening of the new North Stream gas pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level.
The German chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte have symbolically combined the steering wheel of the valve, which carries the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first 1224 km long pipeline linking the region of St Petersburg with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - is due to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the possibility of building a third line ring on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and punctual completion of this huge building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
