All this explains the broad smile of the many Gazprom Managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas pipeline.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe consists of steel with concrete lining, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m deep.
During her construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be balanced.
"A hundred mines had to be removed or destroyed for a precaution," Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream, said.
In addition, stronger measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long hose made of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is interrupted by nothing over the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off Sweden's coast, but project managers have deviated from it because Sweden was little interested in seeing a Russian state company settle in a permanent manner at the level of its coasts.
"In the case of a disaster, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller explained.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the constructors, since the tails were estimated to have a leak per 100,000 years.
The state monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured by both an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation by a seaship, as well as by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, a meter diameter, is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is moved through the gas pressure.
After three complete days of forward movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information about any deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have united their forces to achieve this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E.ON and BASF (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each 9%) are affiliated here.
